details.purpose: Intravascular pressure measurement in jugular vein.

items.items: The character of the jugular pulse.
Observation that JVP changes with changes of abdominal pressure; also known as abdominal jugular reflux.
Indicated the internal jugular vein swelling as a response to increased abdominal pressure, but returning to normal immediately.
Indicated the internal jugular vein swelling as a response to increased abdominal pressure, but being sustained and followed by a slower than normal return to usual levels.
A positive Kussmaul's sign represents the abnormal response where a JVP rises with inspiration.
Normal response where the JVP is lowered during inspiration.
Abnormal response where the JVP rises with inspiration.
Abnormal wave pattern resulting when the atrium contracts against a closed tricuspid valve.
The pressure in a specific location, blood vessel or heart cavity, at a specific phase of the heart or an average over the heart cycle.
The pressure in the internal jugular vein during specific phase of the heart cycle or an average over the heart cycle.
The average over one heart cycle.
The phase of the heart cycle at the time of the measurement
The pressure is much lower than normal or expected.
The pressure is normal or as expected.
The pressure is much higher than normal or expected.
The device used to measure the pressure.
Phase of the heart immediately prior to contraction of the heart.
The phase of the heart immediately prior to filling of the ventricle.
The pressure measueerd is over the whole heart cycle.
The device used to record the measurement.
A waveform representation of the pressure
A multimedia representation of the pressure reading, other than waveforms.
A text comment on the reading.
The location of the pressure measurement.
Other factors that may interfere with interpretation of the measurement.
